definition.value: A derivative of aniline in which the hydrogen at position 3 has been substituted by fluorine. It is used as a pharmaceutical intermediate.
An S-alkyl-CoA having 3-hydroxy-3-methylbutyl as the S-alkyl component.

An N-acetyl-beta-D-glycosaminyl glycopeptide consisting of an N-acetyl-beta-D-glycosaminyl-(1->4)-N-acetylmuramoyl moiety attached to the amino terminus of the tetrapeptide L-alanyl-D-glutamyl-6-carboxy-L-lysyl-D-alanine via an amide linkage.
A naphthylamine carrying the amino group at position 2.
A member of the class of pretetramides in which the only additional substituent is a methyl group at position 6.
An imidazoline that is 2-amino 4,5-dihydro-1H-imidazoline in which one of the exocyclic amino hydrogens has been replaced by a 4-amino-2,6-dichlorophenyl group.
A stilbenol that is stilbene in which the phenyl groups are substituted at positions 3, 5, and 4' by hydroxy groups.

A colchicine that has (S)-configuration. It is a secondary metabolite, has anti-inflammatory properties and is used to treat gout, crystal-induced joint inflammation, familial Mediterranean fever, and many other conditions.
A GDP-sugar having 6-deoxy-L-mannose as the sugar component.
The hydrochloride salt of apraclonidine.
An S-substituted L-cysteine where the S-substituent is specified as a sulfo group.
A fluorobenzoate that is the conjugate base of 4-fluorobenzoic acid.
An alpha-amino acid that is alanine bearing an indol-3-yl substituent at position 3.

A diamminedichloroplatinum compound in which the two ammine ligands and two chloro ligands are oriented in a cis planar configuration around the central platinum ion. An anticancer drug that interacts with, and forms cross-links between, DNA and proteins, it is used as a neoplasm inhibitor to treat solid tumours, primarily of the testis and ovary. Commonly but incorrectly described as an alkylating agent due to its mechanism of action (but it lacks alkyl groups).

An aminoglycoside that is 2-deoxystreptamine that is substituted on the oxygen at position 4 by an (8R)-2-amino-8-O-(4-amino-4-deoxy-alpha-D-glucopyranosyl)-2,3,7-trideoxy-7-(methylamino)-D-glycero-alpha-D-allo-octodialdo-1,5:8,4-dipyranos-1-yl) group.
A broad-spectrum polyketide antibiotic produced by the Streptomyces genus of actinobacteria.
A chlorophenoxyacetic acid that is phenoxyacetic acid in which the ring hydrogens at postions 2, 4 and 5 are substituted by chlorines.
The D-enantiomer of erythrose.
An aryl sulfate that is phenol bearing an O-sulfo substituent.
A derivative of benzoquinone carrying a 5-methyl substituent; and methoxy substituents at positions 2 and 3. The core structure of the ubiquinone group of compounds.
An L-rhamnopyranose having alpha-configuration at the anomeric centre.
A trioxane that is 1,3,5-trioxane substituted by methyl groups at positions 2, 4 and 6.
A member of the class of  barbiturates that is pyrimidine-2,4,6(1H,3H,5H)-trione substituted by an isopropyl and a  prop-1-en-3-yl group at position 5.
A 3beta-sterol having the structure of desmosterol with an extra double bond at C-7--C-8.
An acetylspermidine that is 1,8-diamino-4-azaoctane in which one of the hydrogens of the amino group attached to C-8 is replaced by an acetyl group.
A mannan consisting of repeating D-mannosyl units joined via alpha-(1->6)-linkages.
A trimer of cyanamide, with a 1,3,5-triazine skeleton.
A member of the class of chalcones that is trans-chalcone substituted by a hydroxy group at position 2'.
A member of the class of 7-hydroxyisoflavones that is 7-hydroxyisoflavone substituted by additional hydroxy groups at positions 5, 2' and 4' and a prenyl group at position 6.
A ketohexose often involved in the commercial production of vitamin C. It has been found to occur naturally in grapes.
